uld at least consider the possibility of developing an independent nuclear deterrent. This has been within Australia's capability for decades and it is my understanding that it was seriously considered in the early 50s.<br>
<br>
Under the current arrangement, Australia must rely completely* on the United States to deter any nuclear threat from China or a rogue state. These threats can only become more numerous in the future, and may already be more numerous than is commonly realized. During the Cold War, when the Soviet Union was the threat, reliance on the US made sense. In the murky world of today, and the murkier world of the future, it may be much less certain. <br>
<br>
It is not impossible, perish the thought, that some unfortunate sequence of events could bring an isolationist, pacifist, and anti-nuclear administration to power in the US. There are certainly enough misguided watermelons and fellow-travellers working toward that goal, and they have recently been joined by far-right religious elements. The same might happen in Australia, but such a political catastrophe in Australia would not leave that country, let alone the US, naked against nuclear aggression. If it happened in the US, you would be defenseless through events over which you have no control. Is this acceptable to a sovereign state?<br>
 You can still count on us for now, but are you really willing to bet your national independence on this arrangement continuing forever? <br>
<br>
